𝐃𝐚𝐲 𝟒 – 𝐋𝐞𝐚𝐫𝐧 𝐆𝐞𝐫𝐦𝐚𝐧 𝐀𝟏 𝐰𝐢𝐭𝐡 𝐌𝐞: 𝐇𝐨𝐰 𝐭𝐨 𝐀𝐬𝐤 𝐀𝐠𝐞 + 𝐍𝐮𝐦𝐛𝐞𝐫𝐬 🔢👶🎂
Let’s talk numbers and how to ask someone’s age in German!

Here’s the deal: In German, the structure of asking age is different than in English. Instead of saying "How old are you?", you literally say "How old are you being?"

🗣 Informal (for friends, kids, or people your age):
 Wie alt bist du? – How old are you?
👩‍🏫 Formal (for strangers, teachers, etc.):
 Wie alt sind Sie? – How old are you? (formal)
🧠 To answer, just say:
 Ich bin [Zahl] Jahre alt. – I am [number] years old.
 ➡️ Example: Ich bin einundzwanzig Jahre alt. (I’m 21 years old)

🎯 𝐍𝐮𝐦𝐛𝐞𝐫𝐬 𝟐𝟏–𝟏𝟎𝟎:
👉 21 = einundzwanzig
 👉 35 = fünfunddreißig
 👉 48 = achtundvierzig
 👉 57 = siebenundfünfzig
 👉 66 = sechsundsechzig
 👉 79 = neunundsiebzig
 👉 100 = hundert

Remember: In German, you say the unit before the tens. So 24 = vierundzwanzig (four and twenty)!

